Additional details

Product Description

This Heat Only Thermostat has low voltage controls with a snap-action switch for heating systems. It comes with mounting hardware (wall plate included) and does not require leveling. This manual thermostat controls heating in your home simply and effectively.

From the Manufacturer

For straight-forward temperature control, there's no substitute for Honeywell Home non-digital thermostats. Non-digital thermostats control heating and cooling in your home simply and effectively. Aesthetically pleasing and simple to use, Honeywell Home non-digital thermostats have been the industry standard for over 50 years. For accurate control and quality that's built to last chose from several Honeywell Home designs

Important information

Bulb Voltage

120 volts

From the manufacturer

Simplistic Design and Operation

This Heat Only Thermostat has low voltage controls with a snap-action switch for heating systems. It comes with mounting hardware (wall plate included) and does not require leveling. This manual thermostat controls heating in your home simply and effectively.

  • NOT Compatible with: electric baseboard heat, heat pump systems, or multi stage heating/cooling systems

Easy to install and use

Straightforward temperature control

DIY installation

  • No level needed
  • Snap acting switch (magnetic switch)
  • Comes with mounting hardware (wall plate included)

Bimetal temperature sensor offers simple and hassle-free operation.

Trade just a little of your time for a DIY install project. The included mounting hardware, and quick install guide can have your thermostat up and running quickly.

  • ToolReview
    1.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    No. Not suitable for a millivolt-only (no external power) application.
    Reviewed in the United States on November 13, 2020
    Honeywell Home CT30A1005 Standard Manual Economy Thermostat I see in the Q&A's the manufacturer replied it is suitable for Empire heaters, while a seller said no it isn't. I expect that seller speaks from having had thermostats returned to him as... See more
    Honeywell Home CT30A1005 Standard Manual Economy Thermostat

    I see in the Q&A's the manufacturer replied it is suitable for Empire heaters, while a seller said no it isn't. I expect that seller speaks from having had thermostats returned to him as unusable.

    My observation - not suitable for Empire heaters that need a millivolt thermostat. This seems to be a '2-wire' thermostat, not a millivolt thermostat.

    It generally failed to turn on. Millivolts measured arriving at the thermostat were adequate. I found infinite resistance across its contact points. (That should measure zero when the points appear to be closed). I see 'rated up to 30 volts' on a tag inside. Maybe this needs the usual 24 volts from a transformer. I cleaned the points with electronics solvent. No improvement. Moving the temp lever hot/cold several times is the only way to start the furnace. It just won't come on by itself as the room cooled even when the points appear closed.

    It's incompatible with my new heater that calls for a millivolt thermostat. The new heater:
    'HouseWarmer Slim-Profile Direct Vent Heater with Blower - Natural Gas' is
    Same as - many Empire heaters. I assume its made by Empire.

    So I bought an Empire 'reed switch' thermostat. I see it's different internally. Instead of mechanical points it has a reed assembly similar to a small resistor but glass, bridging between the two terminals. A magnet on the temperature-sensing coil passes by this reed component to trigger its internal points.
    'Cozy Low Voltage Reed Switch Thermostat' looks to be same as the Empire thermostat.

    Advice - Not for use with Empire heaters. Not for use where a Reed Switch is called for.

    Summary - This Honeywell CT30 Series thermostat is not suitable for a heater that has no external voltage source.
